        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-07-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-07-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="521" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d521">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.20211/7–1846: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smith</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-07-18">July 18,
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1312. <gloss target="#t_Sov1">Sov</gloss>. Navy Lieut. Nicolai Redin acquitted
                    July 17 by US Federal Court jury on espionage and conspiracy charges. Further
                        <gloss target="#t_Info1">info</gloss> re trial and newspaper reports will be
                    forwarded <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss>.<note n="19" xml:id="d521fn19">Further information and newspaper clippings were enclosed in instruction
                        1296, July 26, 1946, to Moscow, not printed. Redin’s trial was held in
                        Seattle before Federal District Judge Lloyd Black. On July 17, the jury
                        acquitted Redin on all charges. According to newspaper reports he expressed
                        his thanks for a fair trial.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
